{"title_page": "Poundbury", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name = Poundbury\n|country = England\n|region = South West England\n|static_image_name = File:Queen Mother SQUARE, Poundbury, Dorset.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Queen Mother Square, with Strathmore House (right)\n|population =3500\n|os_grid_reference = SY671549\n|map_type = Dorset\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.7133|-2.466|display=inline,title}}\n|post_town = DORCHESTER\n|postcode_area = DT\n|postcode_district = DT1\n|dial_code = 01305\n|constituency_westminster = [[West Dorset (constituency)|West Dorset]]\n|civil_parish = [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]]\n|unitary_england = [[Dorset (unitary authority)|Dorset]]|shire_county = [[Dorset]]\n}}\n\n'''Poundbury''' is an experimental [[new town]] or [[urban development|urban extension]] on the outskirts of [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] in the [[Counties of England|county]] of [[Dorset]], England. Initiated by architect [[L\u00e9on Krier]] in the spirit of the [[New Urbanism|urban village]], it enjoys the keen endorsement of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], on whose land it is built ([[Duchy of Cornwall]]). Due for completion in 2025, it is expected to house a population of 6,000. Poundbury currently provides employment for over 2,000 people in over 180 businesses.\n\nPoundbury has been praised for reviving the low-rise streetscape built to the human scale, and for echoing traditional local design features. But it has also been criticised as artificially nostalgic, and it has not succeeded in reducing car dependence.\n\n==Mission==\nPoundbury has been built according to the principles of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], who is known for holding strong views challenging the [[post-war]] trends in [[town planning]] that were suburban in character. Since starting in 1993, the town has received both criticism and praise from architects and design critics.\n\nThe development is built to a traditional high-density urban pattern, rather than a suburban one, focused on creating an integrated community of shops, businesses, and private and [[social housing]]. There is no [[zoning]]. The planners say they are designing the development around people rather than the car, and they aim to provide a high-quality environment, from the architecture to the selection of materials, to the signposts, and the [[landscaping]]. To avoid constant construction, utilities are buried in [[common utility duct]]s under the town. Common areas are maintained by a management company to which all residents belong. It consists of 35 percent social housing and is designed for [[sustainable development]],<ref>{{cite news |title=About Poundbury |url=http://www.poundburycommercial.com/about-poundbury/ |accessdate=15 July 2018 |publisher=www.poundburycommercial.com}}</ref> which includes [[carbon neutrality]].<ref>Pentreath, Ben, ''[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/94e6c310-3c8f-11e3-a8c4-00144feab7de.html How the Poundbury project became a model for innovation]'', ''Financial Times'', 1 November 2013</ref>\n\nTo some degree, the project shows similarities with the contemporary [[New Urbanism]] movement. The development brief outlined having a centre built in a classical style and outer neighbourhood areas in a [[Vernacular architecture|vernacular]] style, with design influences taken from the surrounding area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prewettbizley.com/graham-bizley-blog/poundbury|title=Poundbury - What's not to like?}}</ref> The development includes period features such as wrought iron fences, [[portico]]s, gravelled public squares, and 'bricked-up' windows; known as blind windows these traditionally serve an aesthetic function and are widely misattributed to the [[window tax]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Niewitecki|first=Stefan|date=October 2017|title=False Windows \u2013 Yesterday and Today|journal=IOP Conference Series: Materials Science and Engineering|volume=245|issue=5|pages=052066|doi=10.1088/1757-899X/245/5/052066|issn=1757-899X|bibcode=2017MS&E..245e2066N}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gvshp.org/blog/2011/12/23/blurring-the-lines-with-blind-windows/|title=Blurring the Lines with Blind Windows|last=Berman|first=Andrew|date=2011-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Poundbury from Maiden Castle - geograph.org.uk - 401969.jpg|thumb|right|Poundbury as seen from [[Maiden Castle, Dorset|Maiden Castle]]]]\n\nAlthough construction started in October&nbsp;1993,<ref name=\"financial\">{{cite news |title=How the Poundbury project became a model for innovation |url=https://www.ft.com/content/94e6c310-3c8f-11e3-a8c4-00144feab7de |accessdate=12 July 2018 |newspaper=Financial Times}}</ref> the overall plan was conceived in the late 1980s by the [[New Classical architecture|New Classical architect]] and 2003 [[Driehaus Architecture Prize|Driehaus Prize]] winner [[L\u00e9on Krier]], and its development and architectural co-ordination is still ongoing under Krier's direction. It is expected that the four plan phases will be developed over 25&nbsp;years with a total of 2,500&nbsp;dwellings and a population of approximately 6,000.\n\nGreetings card entrepreneur [[Andrew Brownsword]] sponsored the \u00a31&nbsp;million development of the market hall at Poundbury, designed by [[John Simpson (architect)|John Simpson]] and based on early designs, particularly the one in [[Tetbury]].<ref name=\"Telegraph 2001\">{{cite news |first=Giles |last=Worsley |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4721321/A-model-village-grows-up-gracefully.html |title=A model village grows up gracefully |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London, UK |date=30 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nAs of 2018, Poundbury has a population of 3,500 residents.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince of Wales visits Poundbury the 'town that Charles built' |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-11-26/charles-visits-poundbury-the-town-that-charles-built/ |accessdate=31 July 2019 |publisher=ITV |date=26 November 2018}}</ref> The population is expected to increase by 2025 when completed to almost 6,000 residents.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |title=A royal revolution: is Prince Charles's model village having the last laugh? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/oct/27/poundbury-prince-charles-village-dorset-disneyland-growing-community |accessdate=12 July 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Economy and employment==\n[[File:Poundbury (16647130723).jpg|thumb|left|Butter Cross bakery<ref name=\"Guardian\" />]]\nIn 2010, Poundbury increased Dorset's county local economy contributing over \u00a3330million; it is expected to contribute \u00a3500million in the next 15 years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poundbury's \u00a3330million boost to local economy |url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/8318514.poundburys-330million-boost-to-local-economy/ |accessdate=8 January 2019 |date=8 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, more than 2,000 Poundbury residents were working in 180 local businesses.  In 2017, the number of businesses increased to 185, providing 2,345 jobs.<ref name=\"Pound\">{{cite news |title=Meeting the residents and businesses owners of Poundbury |url=http://www.dorsetmagazine.co.uk/people/meeting-the-residents-and-businesses-owners-of-poundbury-1-5452020 |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=Dorset.com |date=27 March 2018}}</ref>  Businesses include a [[Waitrose]] store, a technical company which produces parts for aeroplane wings, and a chocolate factory.\n\nOne notable local employer is the breakfast food manufacturer and exporter [[Dorset Cereals]], which since 2000 has employed more than 100 people at its purpose-built barn factory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dorset Cereals: Changing the world, one breakfast bowl at a time|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/dorset-cereals-changing-the-world-one-breakfast-bowl-at-a-time-7893714.html|work=The Independent|date=28 June 2012}}</ref>  Reportedly there is space for about 80 additional businesses.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poundbury: A look at Prince Charles' sustainable village in Dorset, on its 30th birthday |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/buy/poundbury-look-prince-charles-sustainable-village-dorset-30th/ |accessdate=11 July 2018 |newspaper=Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen visits Waitrose in Prince Charles's village Poundbury |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/28/queen-visits-waitrose-in-prince-charless-village-poundbury/ |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education ==\nPoundbury has two primary schools in the catchment area; The Prince of Wales and Damers First School. The latter was already an existing school in Dorchester but in 2017 relocated to Poundbury, where a new school building was built.<ref>{{cite news |title=School build starts on Prince Charles's Poundbury estate |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-dorset-35213636 |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=BBC |date=2 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Work set to begin on \u00a310million Poundbury school to replace Damers First School in Dorchester |url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/14128348.Work_set_to_begin_on___10million_Poundbury_school/ |publisher=dorsetecho.co.uk |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Schools and education |url=http://www.celebratingpoundbury.co.uk/about-poundbury/schools-education-poundbury-application/ |publisher=celebratingpoundbury.co.uk |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Church==\nIn 2018, the Prince of Wales officially opened Poundbury's first church, the Dorchester Community Church.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince Charles in Poundbury today |url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/17255585.prince-charles-in-poundbury-today/ |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions and landmarks==\n[[File:Poundbury 2019 IMG 9708.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Mother Square]]\nDue to Poundbury's unique looking buildings and plan, the town has been visited by architects, government officials, planners, housebuilders, and developers from around the world.<ref name=\"financial\" />\n\nTourist attractions are centered around the Queen Mother Square, it includes Strathmore House in honour of his grandmother [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]]'s heritage which has been called a replica of [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Look familiar? Prince Charles builds a spectacular house fit for a Queen Mother with Buckingham Palace lookalike tribute to his late grandmother (including eight apartments costing \u00a3650,000 each) |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3789242/A-house-fit-queen-mother-Prince-Charles-builds-spectacular-replica-Buckingham-Palace-tribute-late-grandmother.html |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=Dailymail}}</ref> In 2016, the Queen Mother statue was unveiled at the square by the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen Mother statue unveiled at Poundbury estate |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-dorset-37778512 |accessdate=12 July 2018 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Also in 2016, a pub named the Duchess of Cornwall Inn was opened in honour of his wife, [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Duchess of Cornwall Inn Opens in Poundbury |url=http://duchyofcornwall.org/news/duchess-of-cornwall-inn/ |accessdate=12 July 2018 |date=November 2016}}</ref>\n\nEvery year in August, the Dorset Food & Arts Festival is held at the Queen Mother's Square attracting thousands of people. The festival showcases the town's fine produce and arts and also raises money for charities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thousands go along to enjoy the fare at Dorset Food and Arts Festival in Poundbury |url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/11384456.Thousands_go_along_to_enjoy_the_fare_at_Dorset_Food_and_Arts_Festival_in_Poundbury/ |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=The Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pounbury |url=https://dorsetfestival.org/about-us/about-us-poundbury/ |publisher=dorsetfestival.org |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Celebrate Dorset best at the Dorset food and art festival |url=http://www.celebratingpoundbury.co.uk/celebrate-dorsets-best-dorset-food-arts-festival/ |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and praise ==\n[[File:Middlemarsh Street - geograph.org.uk - 384233.jpg|thumb|Middlemarsh Street]]\nPoundbury's aesthetics have been criticised by several commentators. One described it as \"fake, heartless, authoritarian and grimly cute\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/dec/07/poundbury-prince-charles-communities |title=I'll show you a real carbuncle, Charles |first=Stephen |last=Bayley |work=The Guardian |date=7 December 2008 |quote=To visit Poundbury is to be delivered to the furniture floor of a provincial department store in 1954, translated into architecture. It is fake, heartless, authoritarian and grimly cute.}}</ref>\n\nWriting in ''[[Architect (magazine)|Architect]]'' magazine, Professor [[Witold Rybczynski]] said that \"Poundbury embodies social, economic, and planning innovations that can only be called radical.\"<ref name=arch>{{cite work |url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/design/behind-the-facade-of-prince-charless-poundbury_o |title=Behind the Fa\u00e7ade of Prince Charles's Poundbury |last=Rybczynski |first=Witold |work=[[Architect (magazine)|Architect]] |date=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing New Urbanist principles, Poundbury was intended to reduce [[automobile dependency|car dependency]] and encourage walking, cycling, and public transport.  A survey conducted at the end of the first phase, however, showed that car use was higher in Poundbury than in the surrounding (rural) former district of West Dorset.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Watson, G. |author2=Bentley, I. |author3=Roaf, S. |author4=Smith, P. |year=2004  |title=Learning from Poundbury |series=Research for the West Dorset District Council and the Duchy of Cornwall |publisher=Oxford Brookes University}}</ref> Nonetheless, the community has received positive recognition from New Urbanist publication ''Better Cities and Towns''.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Steuteville, Robert |url=http://bettercities.net/article/20-poundbury-winning-converts-20839 |title=At 20, Poundbury is winning converts |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131110135652/http://bettercities.net/article/20-poundbury-winning-converts-20839 |archive-date=10 November 2013 |magazine=Better Cities and Towns |date=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nBritish architecture and design critic [[Oliver Wainwright]] of ''The Guardian'' states, \"Poundbury, the Prince of Wales\u2019s traditionalist village in Dorset, has long been mocked as a feudal Disneyland. But a growing and diverse community suggests it's getting a lot of things right.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\" />\n\nAccording to English philosopher [[Roger Scruton|Sir Roger Scruton]], \"the proportions are human proportions; the details are restful to the eye. This is not great or original architecture, nor does it try to be; it is a modest attempt to get things right by following patterns and examples laid down by tradition. This is not nostalgia, but knowledge passed on from age to age.\"<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Lockwood, Louise (Director) | date=November 28, 2009 | title=Why Beauty Matters | medium=Television production |time=50:02 | location=United Kingdom | publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:The_Whistling_Witch,_Poundbury.jpg|''The Whistling Witch'' row of shops (2008)\nFile:Dorchester fire station - geograph.org.uk - 1394738.jpg|[[Dorset Fire and Rescue Service]] HQ/Fire station. In 2016 Dorset Fire and Rescue Service merged with Wiltshire Fire and Rescue Service.  This meant that the new services H/Q moved to Salisbury and the Dorset building became support offices and Dorchester Community Fire Station.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dorset and Wiltshire fire services merge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-35927608 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\nFile:Dorset poundbury 01.jpg|Brownsword Hall in Poundbury, designed by architect [[John Simpson (architect)|John Simpson]] and based on earlier traditional designs, particularly one in [[Tetbury]]\nFile:Dorset Cereals factory, Poundbury - geograph.org.uk - 1715303.jpg|Dorset Cereals Factory\nFile:Apartment block, Poundbury - geograph.org.uk - 1587876.jpg|Apartment block \nFile:Holmead Walk - Poundbury - geograph.org.uk - 981485.jpg|Holmead Walk \nFile:Poundbury, new housing at the W end of Dorchester - geograph.org.uk - 31302.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Fairford Leys]] \u2013 a similar project located on the edge of [[Aylesbury]]\n*[[Poundbury Hill]] \u2013 an Iron Age hill fort near Poundbury\n* [[Driehaus Architecture Prize]]\n\n==References==\n*HRH Charles, Prince of Wales: ''[[A Vision of Britain: A Personal View of Architecture]]'' (Doubleday, 1989) {{ISBN|0-385-26903-X}}\n*Leon Krier: ''Architecture: Choice or Fate'' (Andreas Papadakis Publishers, 1998) {{ISBN|1-901092-03-8}}\n*Sandy Mitchell. \"Prince Charles is not your typical radical.\" ''National Geographic''.  May 2006. [http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0605/feature3/index.html]. Retrieved 9/14/06\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Poundbury}}\n*[https://poundbury.co.uk Official Poundbury Website]\n*[https://duchyofcornwall.org/poundbury.html Poundbury] at [[Duchy of Cornwall]] Office\n*[http://www.poundbury.org.uk Unofficial Poundbury business guide and local information]\n{{Charles, Prince of Wales}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1993]]\n[[Category:New Urbanism communities]]\n[[Category:Villages in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Duchy of Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Geography of Dorchester, Dorset]]\n[[Category:New towns in England]]\n[[Category:Neo-Historism]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n[[Category:New Classical architecture]]\n[[Category:New towns started in the 1990s]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name = Poundbury\n|country = England\n|region = South West England\n|static_image_name = File:Queen Mother SQUARE, Poundbury, Dorset.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Queen Mother Square, with Strathmore House (right)\n|population =3500\n|os_grid_reference = SY671549\n|map_type = Dorset\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.7133|-2.466|display=inline,title}}\n|post_town = DORCHESTER\n|postcode_area = DT\n|postcode_district = DT1\n|dial_code = 01305\n|constituency_westminster = [[West Dorset (constituency)|West Dorset]]\n|civil_parish = [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]]\n|unitary_england = [[Dorset (unitary authority)|Dorset]]|shire_county = [[Dorset]]\n}}\n\n'''Poundbury''' is an experimental [[new town]] or [[urban development|urban extension]] on the outskirts of [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] in the [[Counties of England|county]] of [[Dorset]], England. Initiated by architect [[L\u00e9on Krier]] in the spirit of the [[New Urbanism|urban village]], it enjoys the keen endorsement of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], on whose land it is built ([[Duchy of Cornwall]]). Due for completion in 2025, it is expected to house a population of 6,000. Poundbury currently provides employment for over 2,000 people in over 180 businesses.\n\nPoundbury has been praised for reviving the low-rise streetscape built to the human scale, and for echoing traditional local design features. But it has also been criticised as artificially nostalgic, and it has not succeeded in reducing car dependence.\n\n==Mission==\nPoundbury has been built according to the principles of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], who is known for holding strong views challenging the [[post-war]] trends in [[town planning]] that were suburban in character. Since starting in 1993, the town has received both criticism and praise from architects and design critics.\n\nThe development is built to a traditional high-density urban pattern, rather than a suburban one, focused on creating an integrated community of shops, businesses, and private and [[social housing]]. There is no [[zoning]]. The planners say they are designing the development around people rather than the car, and they aim to provide a high-quality environment, from the architecture to the selection of materials, to the signposts, and the [[landscaping]]. To avoid constant construction, utilities are buried in [[common utility duct]]s under the town. Common areas are maintained by a management company to which all residents belong. It consists of 35 percent social housing and is designed for [[sustainable development]],<ref>{{cite news |title=About Poundbury |url=http://www.poundburycommercial.com/about-poundbury/ |accessdate=15 July 2018 |publisher=www.poundburycommercial.com}}</ref> which includes [[carbon neutrality]].<ref>Pentreath, Ben, ''[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/94e6c310-3c8f-11e3-a8c4-00144feab7de.html How the Poundbury project became a model for innovation]'', ''Financial Times'', 1 November 2013</ref>\n\nTo some degree, the project shows similarities with the contemporary [[New Urbanism]] movement. The development brief outlined having a centre built in a classical style and outer neighbourhood areas in a [[Vernacular architecture|vernacular]] style, with design influences taken from the surrounding area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prewettbizley.com/graham-bizley-blog/poundbury|title=Poundbury - What's not to like?}}</ref> The development includes period features such as wrought iron fences, [[portico]]s, gravelled public squares, and 'bricked-up' windows; known as blind windows these traditionally serve an aesthetic function and are widely misattributed to the [[window tax]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Niewitecki|first=Stefan|date=October 2017|title=False Windows \u2013 Yesterday and Today|journal=IOP Conference Series: Materials Science and Engineering|volume=245|issue=5|pages=052066|doi=10.1088/1757-899X/245/5/052066|issn=1757-899X|bibcode=2017MS&E..245e2066N}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gvshp.org/blog/2011/12/23/blurring-the-lines-with-blind-windows/|title=Blurring the Lines with Blind Windows|last=Berman|first=Andrew|date=2011-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Poundbury from Maiden Castle - geograph.org.uk - 401969.jpg|thumb|right|Poundbury as seen from [[Maiden Castle, Dorset|Maiden Castle]]]]\n\nAlthough construction started in October&nbsp;1993,<ref name=\"financial\">{{cite news |title=How the Poundbury project became a model for innovation |url=https://www.ft.com/content/94e6c310-3c8f-11e3-a8c4-00144feab7de |accessdate=12 July 2018 |newspaper=Financial Times}}</ref> the overall plan was conceived in the late 1980s by the [[New Classical architecture|New Classical architect]] and 2003 [[Driehaus Architecture Prize|Driehaus Prize]] winner [[L\u00e9on Krier]], and its development and architectural co-ordination is still ongoing under Krier's direction. It is expected that the four plan phases will be developed over 25&nbsp;years with a total of 2,500&nbsp;dwellings and a population of approximately 6,000.\n\nGreetings card entrepreneur [[Andrew Brownsword]] sponsored the \u00a31&nbsp;million development of the market hall at Poundbury, designed by [[John Simpson (architect)|John Simpson]] and based on early designs, particularly the one in [[Tetbury]].<ref name=\"Telegraph 2001\">{{cite news |first=Giles |last=Worsley |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4721321/A-model-village-grows-up-gracefully.html |title=A model village grows up gracefully |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London, UK |date=30 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nAs of 2018, Poundbury has a population of 3,500 residents.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince of Wales visits Poundbury the 'town that Charles built' |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-11-26/charles-visits-poundbury-the-town-that-charles-built/ |accessdate=31 July 2019 |publisher=ITV |date=26 November 2018}}</ref> The population is expected to increase by 2025 when completed to almost 6,000 residents.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |title=A royal revolution: is Prince Charles's model village having the last laugh? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/oct/27/poundbury-prince-charles-village-dorset-disneyland-growing-community |accessdate=12 July 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Economy and employment==\n[[File:Poundbury (16647130723).jpg|thumb|left|Butter Cross bakery\"<ref name=\"Guardian\" />]]\nIn 2010, Poundbury increased Dorset's county local economy contributing over \u00a3330million; it is expected to contribute \u00a3500million in the next 15 years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poundbury's \u00a3330million boost to local economy |url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/8318514.poundburys-330million-boost-to-local-economy/ |accessdate=8 January 2019 |date=8 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, more than 2,000 Poundbury residents were working in 180 local businesses.  In 2017, the number of businesses increased to 185, providing 2,345 jobs.<ref name=\"Pound\">{{cite news |title=Meeting the residents and businesses owners of Poundbury |url=http://www.dorsetmagazine.co.uk/people/meeting-the-residents-and-businesses-owners-of-poundbury-1-5452020 |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=Dorset.com |date=27 March 2018}}</ref>  Businesses include a [[Waitrose]] store, a technical company which produces parts for aeroplane wings, and a chocolate factory.\n\nOne notable local employer is the breakfast food manufacturer and exporter [[Dorset Cereals]], which since 2000 has employed more than 100 people at its purpose-built barn factory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dorset Cereals: Changing the world, one breakfast bowl at a time|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/dorset-cereals-changing-the-world-one-breakfast-bowl-at-a-time-7893714.html|work=The Independent|date=28 June 2012}}</ref>  Reportedly there is space for about 80 additional businesses.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poundbury: A look at Prince Charles' sustainable village in Dorset, on its 30th birthday |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/buy/poundbury-look-prince-charles-sustainable-village-dorset-30th/ |accessdate=11 July 2018 |newspaper=Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen visits Waitrose in Prince Charles's village Poundbury |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/28/queen-visits-waitrose-in-prince-charless-village-poundbury/ |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education ==\nPoundbury has two primary schools in the catchment area; The Prince of Wales and Damers First School. The latter was already an existing school in Dorchester but in 2017 relocated to Poundbury, where a new school building was built.<ref>{{cite news |title=School build starts on Prince Charles's Poundbury estate |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-dorset-35213636 |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=BBC |date=2 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Work set to begin on \u00a310million Poundbury school to replace Damers First School in Dorchester |url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/14128348.Work_set_to_begin_on___10million_Poundbury_school/ |publisher=dorsetecho.co.uk |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Schools and education |url=http://www.celebratingpoundbury.co.uk/about-poundbury/schools-education-poundbury-application/ |publisher=celebratingpoundbury.co.uk |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Church==\nIn 2018, the Prince of Wales officially opened Poundbury's first church, the Dorchester Community Church.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince Charles in Poundbury today |url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/17255585.prince-charles-in-poundbury-today/ |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions and landmarks==\n[[File:Poundbury 2019 IMG 9708.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Mother Square]]\nDue to Poundbury's unique looking buildings and plan, the town has been visited by architects, government officials, planners, housebuilders, and developers from around the world.<ref name=\"financial\" />\n\nTourist attractions are centered around the Queen Mother Square, it includes Strathmore House in honour of his grandmother [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]]'s heritage which has been called a replica of [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Look familiar? Prince Charles builds a spectacular house fit for a Queen Mother with Buckingham Palace lookalike tribute to his late grandmother (including eight apartments costing \u00a3650,000 each) |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3789242/A-house-fit-queen-mother-Prince-Charles-builds-spectacular-replica-Buckingham-Palace-tribute-late-grandmother.html |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=Dailymail}}</ref> In 2016, the Queen Mother statue was unveiled at the square by the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen Mother statue unveiled at Poundbury estate |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-dorset-37778512 |accessdate=12 July 2018 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Also in 2016, a pub named the Duchess of Cornwall Inn was opened in honour of his wife, [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Duchess of Cornwall Inn Opens in Poundbury |url=http://duchyofcornwall.org/news/duchess-of-cornwall-inn/ |accessdate=12 July 2018 |date=November 2016}}</ref>\n\nEvery year in August, the Dorset Food & Arts Festival is held at the Queen Mother's Square attracting thousands of people. The festival showcases the town's fine produce and arts and also raises money for charities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thousands go along to enjoy the fare at Dorset Food and Arts Festival in Poundbury |url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/11384456.Thousands_go_along_to_enjoy_the_fare_at_Dorset_Food_and_Arts_Festival_in_Poundbury/ |accessdate=12 July 2018 |publisher=The Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pounbury |url=https://dorsetfestival.org/about-us/about-us-poundbury/ |publisher=dorsetfestival.org |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Celebrate Dorset best at the Dorset food and art festival |url=http://www.celebratingpoundbury.co.uk/celebrate-dorsets-best-dorset-food-arts-festival/ |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and praise ==\n[[File:Middlemarsh Street - geograph.org.uk - 384233.jpg|thumb|Middlemarsh Street]]\nPoundbury's aesthetics have been criticised by several commentators. One described it as \"fake, heartless, authoritarian and grimly cute\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/dec/07/poundbury-prince-charles-communities |title=I'll show you a real carbuncle, Charles |first=Stephen |last=Bayley |work=The Guardian |date=7 December 2008 |quote=To visit Poundbury is to be delivered to the furniture floor of a provincial department store in 1954, translated into architecture. It is fake, heartless, authoritarian and grimly cute.}}</ref>\n\nWriting in ''[[Architect (magazine)|Architect]]'' magazine, Professor [[Witold Rybczynski]] said that \"Poundbury embodies social, economic, and planning innovations that can only be called radical.\"<ref name=arch>{{cite work |url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/design/behind-the-facade-of-prince-charless-poundbury_o |title=Behind the Fa\u00e7ade of Prince Charles's Poundbury |last=Rybczynski |first=Witold |work=[[Architect (magazine)|Architect]] |date=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing New Urbanist principles, Poundbury was intended to reduce [[automobile dependency|car dependency]] and encourage walking, cycling, and public transport.  A survey conducted at the end of the first phase, however, showed that car use was higher in Poundbury than in the surrounding (rural) former district of West Dorset.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Watson, G. |author2=Bentley, I. |author3=Roaf, S. |author4=Smith, P. |year=2004  |title=Learning from Poundbury |series=Research for the West Dorset District Council and the Duchy of Cornwall |publisher=Oxford Brookes University}}</ref> Nonetheless, the community has received positive recognition from New Urbanist publication ''Better Cities and Towns''.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Steuteville, Robert |url=http://bettercities.net/article/20-poundbury-winning-converts-20839 |title=At 20, Poundbury is winning converts |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131110135652/http://bettercities.net/article/20-poundbury-winning-converts-20839 |archive-date=10 November 2013 |magazine=Better Cities and Towns |date=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nBritish architecture and design critic [[Oliver Wainwright]] of ''The Guardian'' states, \"Poundbury, the Prince of Wales\u2019s traditionalist village in Dorset, has long been mocked as a feudal Disneyland. But a growing and diverse community suggests it's getting a lot of things right.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\" />\n\nAccording to English philosopher [[Roger Scruton|Sir Roger Scruton]], \"the proportions are human proportions; the details are restful to the eye. This is not great or original architecture, nor does it try to be; it is a modest attempt to get things right by following patterns and examples laid down by tradition. This is not nostalgia, but knowledge passed on from age to age.\"<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Lockwood, Louise (Director) | date=November 28, 2009 | title=Why Beauty Matters | medium=Television production |time=50:02 | location=United Kingdom | publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:The_Whistling_Witch,_Poundbury.jpg|''The Whistling Witch'' row of shops (2008)\nFile:Dorchester fire station - geograph.org.uk - 1394738.jpg|[[Dorset Fire and Rescue Service]] HQ/Fire station. In 2016 Dorset Fire and Rescue Service merged with Wiltshire Fire and Rescue Service.  This meant that the new services H/Q moved to Salisbury and the Dorset building became support offices and Dorchester Community Fire Station.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dorset and Wiltshire fire services merge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-35927608 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>\nFile:Dorset poundbury 01.jpg|Brownsword Hall in Poundbury, designed by architect [[John Simpson (architect)|John Simpson]] and based on earlier traditional designs, particularly one in [[Tetbury]]\nFile:Dorset Cereals factory, Poundbury - geograph.org.uk - 1715303.jpg|Dorset Cereals Factory\nFile:Apartment block, Poundbury - geograph.org.uk - 1587876.jpg|Apartment block \nFile:Holmead Walk - Poundbury - geograph.org.uk - 981485.jpg|Holmead Walk \nFile:Poundbury, new housing at the W end of Dorchester - geograph.org.uk - 31302.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Fairford Leys]] \u2013 a similar project located on the edge of [[Aylesbury]]\n*[[Poundbury Hill]] \u2013 an Iron Age hill fort near Poundbury\n* [[Driehaus Architecture Prize]]\n\n==References==\n*HRH Charles, Prince of Wales: ''[[A Vision of Britain: A Personal View of Architecture]]'' (Doubleday, 1989) {{ISBN|0-385-26903-X}}\n*Leon Krier: ''Architecture: Choice or Fate'' (Andreas Papadakis Publishers, 1998) {{ISBN|1-901092-03-8}}\n*Sandy Mitchell. \"Prince Charles is not your typical radical.\" ''National Geographic''.  May 2006. [http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0605/feature3/index.html]. Retrieved 9/14/06\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Poundbury}}\n*[https://poundbury.co.uk Official Poundbury Website]\n*[https://duchyofcornwall.org/poundbury.html Poundbury] at [[Duchy of Cornwall]] Office\n*[http://www.poundbury.org.uk Unofficial Poundbury business guide and local information]\n{{Charles, Prince of Wales}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1993]]\n[[Category:New Urbanism communities]]\n[[Category:Villages in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Duchy of Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Geography of Dorchester, Dorset]]\n[[Category:New towns in England]]\n[[Category:Neo-Historism]]\n[[Category:1993 estab